ductor longus; lateral = sartorius","Superior = adductor longus; medial = sartorius; lateral = inguinal ligament"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct borders of the femoral triangle are: \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior = inguinal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial = adductor longus\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral = sartorius\u003C/strong\u003E. The femoral triangle is a key anatomical area in the upper thigh, important for its contents, including the femoral nerve, artery, and vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior = sartorius\u003C/strong\u003E - The sartorius forms the lateral border, not the superior\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial = sartorius\u003C/strong\u003E - The sartorius forms the lateral border, not the medial\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral = inguinal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - The inguinal ligament forms the superior border, not the lateral\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior = adductor longus\u003C/strong\u003E - The adductor longus forms the medial border, not the superior\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The femoral triangle is an anatomical region of the upper thigh.","The borders of the femoral triangle are the inguinal ligament superiorly, the adductor longus medially, and the sartorius laterally.","Understanding the anatomy of the femoral triangle is important for procedures such as catheterisation and understanding vascular supply."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 